    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<h2>tl;dr</h2>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>java.time.Year.of( 2014 ).atDay( 34 ).getMonth()\n</code></pre>\n<h2>Modern Java</h2>\n<p>In Java 8+, use the <em>java.time</em> classes.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>34 which means its 3rd day of February</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Use <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/25/docs/api/java.base/java/time/Year.html#atDay(int)\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>Year#atDay</code></a>, passing a number 1-365 or 1-366 in leap years. Automatically accounts for Leap Year.</p>\n<pre><code>LocalDate date = Year.of( 2014 ).atDay( 34 ) ;\n</code></pre>\n<p>If you want just the month, interrogate the <code>LocalDate</code> object.</p>\n<pre><code>Month month = date.getMonth() ;\n</code></pre>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I searched in Calendar</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Never use the terribly-flawed legacy classes like <code>Calendar</code>, <code>Date</code>, <code>Timestamp</code>, <code>SimpleDateFormat</code>, etc. Use only <em>java.time</em>.</p>\n"
  } ],
